The paper focuses on benchmarking community detection methods on empirical social network data, which falls under the scope of social network analysis and machine learning. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing) are the most likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the difficulties in constructing benchmarks based on digitally extracted network data, which relates to data science and data mining, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also discusses the performance of algorithms, which falls under the scope of machine learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the differences between social media data and hand-curated datasets, which falls under the scope of sociology and anthropology, making cs.SOC (Computational Social Science) a possible sub-category.
